definition.value: An organic anion that is the conjugate base of (4S)-2,3-dehydroleucopelargonidin, obtained by deprotonation of the 3-hydroxy group. It is the major microspecies at pH 7.3 (according to Marvin v 6.2.0.).
Any 3'-hydroxyflavanone with lacking a substituent at position 5'.
Any EC 2.4.2.* (pentosyltransferase) inhibitor that interferes with the action of amidophosphoribosyltransferase (EC 2.4.2.14).
Any EC 6.3.5.* (carbon-nitrogen ligases with glutamine as amido-N-donor) inhibitor that interferes with the action of NAD(+) synthase (glutamine-hydrolysing) (EC 6.3.5.1).

A trisaccharide derivative consisting of an alpha-L-rhamnosyl residue glycosidically linked to a 5-aminopentyl group and which carries at O-3 a beta-D-glucosyl-(1->3)-alpha-L-rhamnosyl disaccharide unit.

A pentacyclic triterpenoid that is olean-12-ene in which the hydrogens at the 3beta and 6beta positions have been replaced by hydroxy groups. Found in the seeds of the downy thorn-apple, Datura innoxia.
Any EC 6.3.5.* (carbon-nitrogen ligases with glutamine as amido-N-donor) inhibitor that interferes with the action of asparagine synthase (glutamine-hydrolysing), EC 6.3.5.4.
A disaccharide derivative consisting of an alpha-D-glucosyl residue glycosidically linked to a 5-aminopentyl group and which carries at O-6 an alpha-D-glucosyluronic acid residue.

A tetrasaccharide derivative consisting of an alpha-L-rhamnosyl residue glycosidically linked to a 5-aminopentyl group and which carries at O-3 a beta-L-rhamnosyl-(1->4)-beta-D-glucosyl-(1->3)-alpha-L-rhamnosyl trisaccharide unit.
A hydroxy fatty-acyl-CoA that results from the formal condensation of the thiol group of coenzyme A with the carboxy group of 2-hydroxydecanoic acid.

A linear tetrasaccharide derivative consisting of an alpha-L-rhamnosyl residue glycosidically linked to a 5-aminopentyl group and which carries at O-3 an alpha-D-glucuronosyl-(1->6)-alpha-D-glucosyl-(1->2)-alpha-L-rhamnosyl trisaccharide unit.
An abietane diterpenoid that is ferruginol in which the methylene group para to the phenolic hydroxy group has been substituted by an oxo group.
An abietane diterpenoid that is sugiol in which the hydrogen ortho to the phenolic hydroxy group has been replaced by a hydroxy group.
An abietane diterpenoid that is 11-hydroxysugiol in which one of the hydrogens of the methyl group attached to a ring junction has been replaced by a hydroxy group.
A hydroxy fatty-acyl-CoA that results from the formal condensation of the thiol group of coenzyme A with the carboxy group of 2-hydroxyisovaleric acid.
An abietane diterpenoid that is ferruginol in which a hydrogen of the bridgehead methyl group and the hydrogen ortho to the phenolic hydroxy group have both been replaced by hydroxy groups.
A pimarane diterpenoid in which the hydrogen at position 3beta has been replaced by a hydroxy group.
A diterpenoid that is ent-cassa-12,15-diene in which the hydrogen at position 2beta has been replaced by a hydroxy group.
A diterpenoid that is ent-cassa-12,15-diene in which the hydrogens at positions 2beta and 3beta have been replaced by hydroxy groups.
A diterpenoid that is ent-cassa-12,15-diene in which the methylene hydrogens at position 2 have been replaced by a keto group.
A diterpenoid that is ent-cassa-12,15-diene carrying oxo and hydroxy substituents at positions 2 and 3beta respectively.
A member of the class of octahydronaphthalenes that is drimenol in which a hydrogen of the allylic methyl group has been replaced by a hydroxy group.
A tetracyclic triterpenoid that is 4,9-cyclo-9,10-secocholesta-5,24-diene substituted by methyl groups at positions 9beta, 10, and 14, and by hydroxy groups at positions 1 and 11alpha.
A tetracyclic triterpenoid that is cucurbitadienol in which the methylene hydrogens at position 11 have been replaced by an oxo group.

A tetracyclic triterpenoid that is cucurbitadienol in which the side-chain double bond (position 24-25) has undergone formal oxidation to introduce hydroxy groups at positions 24 and 25 (the 24R stereoisomer). It is a biometabolite of mogrosides found in Siraitia grosvenorii.
A mogroside that is mogrol in which the hydroxyl hydrogen at position 3 has been replaced by a beta-D-glucosyl residue.

A branched polysaccharide composed of a backbone of repeating beta-L-rhamnosyl-(1->4)-beta-D-glucosyl-(1->3)-[alpha-D-glucuronosyl-(1->6)-alpha-D-glucosyl-(1->2)]-alpha-L-rhamnosyl-(1->3)-alpha-L-rhamnosyl units, joined by (1->3) linkages. The repeating unit is that of the Streptococcus pneumoniae serotype 2 capsular polysaccharide.
Any compound that interferes with bacterial communication (quorum sensing, QS).
An L-lysine derivative arising from amide formation between N-2 of L-lysine and the carboxy group of alpha-D-galactopyranuronic acid.
A succinate ester in which only one of the carboxy groups of succinic acid has been esterified.
An ammonium ion resulting from the protonation of the tertiary amino group of AZD1979.  A melanin concentrating hormone receptor 1 (MCHr1) antagonist.
A diol resulting from hydrolysis of the oxetane ring of AZD1979.
An organyl group that is the functional group of taurine attaching at the nitrogen
Any alkene having cis-geometry about the double bond.
A hydroxy fatty-acyl-CoA that results from the formal condensation of the thiol group of coenzyme A with the carboxy group of 2-hydroxyheptadecanoic acid
A hydroxy fatty-acyl-CoA that results from the formal condensation of the thiol group of coenzyme A with the carboxy group of 2-hydroxyicosanoic acid
A hydroxy fatty-acyl-CoA that results from the formal condensation of the thiol group of coenzyme A with the carboxy group of 2-hydroxydodecanoic acid.
A hydroxy fatty-acyl-CoA that results from the formal condensation of the thiol group of coenzyme A with the carboxy group of 2-hydroxytetradecanoic acid.

A hydroxycalciol that is calcitriol which has undergone formal oxidative coupling at positions 20 and 23 to the hydroxy group and methyl group, respectively, of methanol to afford the corresponding oxolane ring (the 20S,23S stereoisomer). It is a superagonist of the vitamin D nuclear receptor in vitro, but is as calcemic in vivo as the natural ligand.

A hydroxycalciol that is calcitriol which has undergone formal oxidative coupling at positions 20 and 23 to the hydroxy group and methyl group, respectively, of methanol to afford the corresponding oxolane ring (the 20S,23R stereoisomer). It is less calcemic towards the vitamin D nuclear receptor than 1alpha,25-dihydroxyvitamin D3 in vivo.
A hydroxycalciol that is a synthetic analogue of vitamin D3 which contains an oxolane ring and exhibits weak vitamin D receptor agonist activity
A hydroxycalciol that is a synthetic analogue of vitamin D3 which contains an oxolane ring and exhibits weak vitamin D receptor agonist activity.

A C-glycosyl compound that is 3,4,5-trihydroxycyclohexa-2,5-dien-1-one which is substituted by beta-D-glucosyl groups at positions 2 and 4, and by a p-hydroxycinnamoyl group at position 6. It is the main bioactive compound of a traditional Chinese medicine obtained from safflower (Carthamus tinctorius).
A hydroxycalciol that is a synthetic analogue of vitamin D3 which contains an oxolane ring and exhibits weak vitamin D receptor agonist activity.
An organophosphate oxoanion obtained by deprotonation of the diphosphate OH groups of nerylneryl diphosphate; major species at pH 7.3.
A diterpenyl phosphate that is the O-diphospho derivative of (-)-kolavenol
A diterpenyl phosphate that is the O-diphospho derivative of (+)-kolavenol
An acyl-CoA that results from the formal condensation of the thiol group of coenzyme A with the carboxy group of L-firefly luciferin.
